license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
A playful vase or flower pot.
Made from a four generation binary tree, with a two generation cavity. Images show a preview render of the Ceramics look and a black ABS version printed using an Up! I designed this for the GrabCAD/Figulo Ceramics challenge, but I missed the deadline. Since it was intended to be shared, here it is too :-) Wall thickness should be enough for professional ceramics printers.
So I guess it will print fine on most home printers. To support my design efforts you can also buy the ceramics version from my Shapeways Shop here:
http://www.shapeways.com/model/621640/BinaryRoots.html

I use an Up! printer myself, so I just load and print it.
Up! settings that worked for me: Z Resolution: 0.3mm
Base height: 2mm
Part Angle<: 45 Deg
Part Surface: 3 Layers
Fill: Loose
Support Dense: 3 layers
Space: 10 Lines
Area>: 5mm2
Angle<: 50 Deg Stable support: On
Unsolid model: On
Raft: On
Speed: Fine While it fits on the platform as oriented in the file, I chose to rotate it 45 on the z-axis before printing, just to be safe. I used the apply-thin-ABS-sludge-to-platform method to prevent curling/warping. I lack in-depth knowledge about other home printers, but I think it will pose no real problems.
Or just use a professional print site and have it printed for you. If the polygon count is too high for your software, you can use free meshlab to reduce using the quadric edge collapse decimation filter.

Here is two kinds of forends that I designed, it is intended for use in carbine form. There is one that simply insulates the cold coming from the air cylinder, from going into your hands. And the other that has a flat bottom and a hole for swivel stud, if you want to attach a bipod to the already small airgun. Since it is a light airgun attaching a light bipod should give that extra stability when shooting off a table.

It simply slides over the main tube.

I would print with 4 outer layers and 30% infill for Rigidity and to save filament.

This is my entry for the Teal Drone Remix Challenge. It works with what is called persistence of vision. As the drone fly's by you should be able to see an image rendered by a strip of led lights. You can find the part list, wiring diagram and everything else you need in adafruit's supernova poi project. This model is made to fit all the parts listed there.

https://learn.adafruit.com/supernova-poi/

I decided to put the LED strip on an angled fin because as the drone fly's forward it should also lean forward. At 80mph The image should be super clear.

I hope whoever wins gives this a shot, I would love to see pictures if anyone does :)

Thank you for your consideration.

Update 1: I put up POV_v5, redesigned so it only needs minimal supports. The fin should be able to support itself now.
Update 2: I also made a long version for extended led strips, if anyone is interested in that. I'm not sure it will fly as well, unlike the original the center of mass is moved up and off center.

This is a mailbox that's first modeled in SolidWorks in order for it to be cut using laser cutter and then assembled together using joinery and gorilla glue. description.text:
This model has been deprecated in favor of the Version 2 model which has changed and is more complete. It may be found at:

Version 2

This is my rendition of the SLS (Space Launch System) Interim Cryogenic Propulsion Stage.

This is meant for educational and display purposes. I tried to get the proportions as close as possible, but information on these things is a bit difficult for me to get. So if there is a NASA engineer out there who can get me the actual dimensions, I would be able to do a more precise model. Additionally, I attempted to design it so it may be displayed entirely closed or partially open for explanation, like the cover picture.

I decided that it was sitting in my archives long enough and if folks want me to continue adding or refining this model, please let me know. I am still working on the fold out solar panels and everything higher than the ICPS (crew capsule, etc).

NOTE: All the models are sized at 4x scale. So if you want to print it on 300 mm circular bed, you will need to scale down each part to 25% the size it is imported. I have not attempted to scale it down further, so you are on your own there.

I did not go though the detailed assembly instruction process on this one yet, like I did with my other models. But would do so given an enthusiastic response. I plan on uploading it to the NASA site after I have refined it a bit more.

Also, if you want to use the Orion Capsule from the NASA site, here are some tips.

  • If scaling down my model to 25%, you will need to scale up the NASA Orion capsule to 735%
  • If scaling down my model to 20%, you will need to scale up the NASA Orion Capsule to 585%

If you attempt to build this and are missing a part, please let me know. I had a couple versions of things and may have been missed during the upload process.

Cheers!

This is a OpenSCAD script for creating a bunch of sticks. Each stick is numbered and each stick is a different length. The lengths are incremented according to the user's input.

Laser cut or 3D print the sticks and pass them out to students. Students will measure the sticks and enter or record an answer. You can check their work based on the number of the stick which corresponds to a measurement. If the students figure out the relationship, they're probably beyond needing to learn how to use a ruler.

Students need practice making linear measurements with rulers. If you just pass out a bunch of objects, students will cheat. This method lets you create an individual set of sticks for each student to measure. You don't need to measure every object, as the lengths are generated programatically.

• Each student will get 3-4 numbered sticks and a ruler.
  • Students will measure their sticks and write down the lengths.
  • Students will enter the stick number and corresponding length into a google form and submit.
  • Students are graded on their accuracy.

• These sticks, laser cut. Recommend 3-4 for each student.

description.text:
It was finally time to pick a glue to use when assembling a few different projects over the Halloween weekend. There was a slight problem, though. Or a few problems. Problem 1 - I had no idea what glue to use for plastic. Problem 2 - these projects were using multiple kinds of plastic, which can be notoriously hard to fuse together.

I've used PlasticWeld in the past, but it's a pain to use, mildly toxic, and the last bottle I had dried up years ago. A trip to the craft store ensued, with dire consequences: there are a lot of different glues, and all of them make claims of bonding anything to anything. So I did what
any curious person with very little free time on their hands would do: set myself up to systematically test as many different glues as I could get my hands on.

The tests are fairly straightforward:

  • Test how well each glue bonds together three different types of plastic: ABS, PLA, and PET
  • Each glue and material combination will undergo two different tests: a load test and a shear test

The load test stresses how well the glue forms a solid and strong layer between two pieces of plastic. The shear test looks at how well the materials and glue stand up to being ripped apart, like tearing off a band-aid.

These tiles are labeled for PLA, ABS, PET, and TPE, as well as having a blank tile.

description.text:
This is my entry to the Teal Drone cover challenge. The purpose of my modification was to add a small tray to the top with slots for a strap on the sides, in order to hold in a wide range of sizes of weather radiosondes. This would allow for anyone with the modification and a functioning radiosonde and receiver to fly their drone to a desired location and utilize the sensors on the radiosonde to measure anything they might want to know. If used in place of weather balloons, this could mean much faster measurements and retrieval of the radiosonde, as the drone could be flown to wherever needed and simply returned once the measurements were made.

Unfortunately, as a result of the propellers on the drone stirring up the surrounding air, it likely couldn't be used to measure wind speed or other data points that are affected by the movement of the air. However, temperature, humidity, air pressure, and any other number of things could still be conveniently measured with this.
Created using Fusion 360.

print_settings.Notes:: I found that a heavier infill allowed for a smoother top surface. I had to do some witchcraft to get this to work the way i wanted. I edited the gcode so that it would print the base, then do the ironing from cura as if that was the last layer. that way it ironed in smooth perpendicular lines instead of the original file cura created where it would iron everything on that layer except where the designs where, creating a not so smooth wacky pattern. Then I paused the print, changed filament colors, and when it resumed i had the g code keep printing the design over the last ironed layer. I tried it with the designs ironed as well but found it made it even messier. I printed mine in black abs for the base as well as red abs for the designs. PLA will most likely smooth properly without having to perform witchcraft on the gcode file

title: Sony HDR-AS50R stand for RM-LVR3 remote monitor

description.text:
I've got the Sony HDR-AS50R with the live view remote. The monitor remote came with a tripod cradle and a watchband. So I decided to make a little table stand that would use the cradle (that has standard 1/4-20 photo thread). This is a very simple snap-on design. You need some sort of 1/4-20 tripod screw or just a screw from home depot. I've got mine from some old tripod I believe.
My screw has 15.5 mm long shaft so the thickness of part 2 is adapted for this. sony_holder2_15mmscrew.stl
The second version sony_holder2_10mmscrew.stl is for the small 10.5mm shaft screws. The big screw is probably a better choice if you have one. Those two lengths are most typical.
The bottom has also a thread for the tripod mount, just in case. You simply snap on the two parts - it is very tight fit as it is not meant to be disassembled.

Hope this may came useful for someone.

title: CR-10 X & Y Tensionser Remix Kit

description.text:
I really liked the kits donnyb99 made but ran into some issues with the bearings causing the belt to rub on the inside of the frame. I started by just tweaking one of the pullers and ended up redesigning most of the parts. These parts are designed to use 4 6-32 screws 6 nuts and the bearings from each stock belt pulley/tensionser assembly. No further hardware is necessary. If you have any questions about the parts or run into issues with the design, fee free to send me a message or leave a comment.

NOTE:
This kit works best when you have replace the stock belts with ones that are slightly longer. There will be some complications with reattaching the belt once these pulley assemblies are installed. I would recommend to replace the belts with longer ones or cut off the metal retaining tabs on one end of the stock belt and replace it with a removable printed clip found here, https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2479414.

title: Carbon Fiber Drone Gimbal for CNC Cutting

description.text:
This is a fairly straightforward gimbal for CNC cutting out of carbon fiber or a similar material. It's based around T-Motor (rctigermotor.com) 4106 motors, which I use with a simplebgc 32bit rev2 controller and navio2 controller. It is intended to be cut out of a combination of 1mm and 2mm carbon fiber, and there is a layer and cut file for each. I used a 0.6mm bit, with the CF clamped to 1/4" hardwood around 1/4" foamcore to allow me to run the bit out at full depth (to reduce stress at the shank interface where they usually break if you're cutting with the tip of the bit).

If you would like one cut for you, just contact me and I can come up with a reasonable price depending on what your needs are.

description.text:
If you own a Turnigy 9x V2 transmitter with the original HF module you might have been upset about the fact that the module can't be removed because of the antenna built into the transmitter case. Here is the solution: an antenna mount adapter for the back of the module... and a cap to close the hole in the transmitter when the antenna has moved. All you have to do are the following steps:
  • Print the parts
  • Open the module, unsolder the antenna and remove the module
  • Open the transmitter case, remove the little screw from the antenna mount, remove the complete antenna and reassemble the transmitter
  • Shorten the little screw you have just removed, insert the antenna into the printed part and mount it with the shortened screw
  • Remove the alloy label from the module cover, drill a hole for the antenna cable, solder the cable to the pcb and close the module case.
  • Glue the printed part with the antenna to the back of the module aligned with the upper edge of the plain you removed the label from
  • Put the module back in place and mount the cap onto the old antenna's hole
    • You're done!

title: In-Ceiling Speaker Enclosure for Recessed Lighting Fixture
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I made these enclosures to utilize the Tectonic Elements TEBM65C20F-8 3-1/2" BMR drivers mounted in the 6" recessed lighting housings though out my (rented) apartment. With a small amplifier and a Chromecast Audio (for each speaker), I have a non-destructive way to implement in-ceiling whole-house audio.

Other speaker designs linked here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2608897

The brackets on the side are for adjusting the final depth of the speaker in the ceiling using M3 hardware. They sit on the integral brackets present in my fixtures, though I'm not sure how standard that design is. You will have to remove the shroud and socket-mount bar, etc.

I went through a few cover plate designs, and settled on the one provided - it is meant to simply friction fit around the speaker body.

The enclosure volume is, of course, limited by the space afforded in the light housing, which must also fit an E26 to Type A outlet adapter, a small DC power supply, the amplifier, and the Chromecast Audio. This is the reason for the wider base on the enclosure; it acts to hold these components above the speaker once in place. It's less than ideal, and a bit of a pain installing it all, but works well for me in the end, given the constraints. An integrated DC power supply/E26 base would make things much cleaner and easier, but I have yet to find or make one.

Main body and cover print without supports, but the small height-adjustment piece will need them.

Dem Schriftdesigner Rudolf Koch ging es ähnlich. Er hatte ein Postkarte entworfen, die er Leuten schickte, die eine Gratisprobe seiner Kunst wollten. Hier also das Motiv von Kochs Postkarte, zum 3D-drucken und verteilen. Natürlich auch bei anderen Gelegenheiten einsetzbar. Alles auf eigene Gefahr.

Es gibt verschiedene Versionen:

  • Rudolf Kochs Antwort, positiv.stl: Für Filamentwechsel beim Druck.
  • Rudolf Kochs Antwort, schnell.stl: Ohne Tricks am Stück zu drucken, hat aber sichtbare Verbindungen zwischen den Wörtern und Buchstaben.

title: Hotend Micrometer Height Ajuster for 20/20 & 20/40 Extrusion

description.text:
This is a compact new version of my popular Anet A-8 Micrometer Height adjuster https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2185918
Its been designed to be a carriage for 20/20 & 20/40 Aluminium extrusion , with 2 sets of holes for M5 bolts to mount the track wheels . It has a complete mounting system for an E3D-V6 hotend & fans, or you can design your own hot end mounts to screw onto the height adjusting slider .

You will need some M3 & M5 Nuts & bolts , extruder track rollers & some 5/16 unf threaded rod & nuts & a spring .

A piece of 8mm x 1mm fine pitch threaded rod ( or 5/16 UNF can be used too) x 110mm long & 3 nuts are needed for the variable height adjuster .A thumb wheel with 10 graduated l markings is used to adjust the height . This gives a resolution of 0.1mm ( 0.004") per graduation & allows the head 12mm of variable height adjustment .A compression spring 25mm long x 10mm dia is used to take all backlash out of the design , as well stop any vibrations
Adjustments can be made while the machine is printing , so if a brim layer appears to be slightly too high or low , it can be adjusted while printing to get the first layer down perfect.
The 2 dovetail wedge parts should be a neat , almost a little tight , so there is no movement or vibration between the 2 parts .
If they are too tight , just pear some plastic away with a sharp knife until the fit is correct .
M3 screws & captive nuts allow the bottom rollers to be ajusted to tension them into the track & provide zero lash .The photos are fairly self explanatory . The Parts are mounted on a modified Anet E10 , but will fit any 20/20 & 20/40 extrusion on other machines.

Purchasing pre- assembled track wheels is the best option , but if you want to buy bearings & print the wheels they are avaliable to print here.
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:611025

There are plenty of E3D-V6 fan mounts & air nozzles to download to suit your needs.

If you Find this useful please Like & post some finished photos .

Added youtube vid https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FZPFHl9lBNI

title: Zimpure Adaptor for Scalar S / L / XL Premium 3D printers

description.text:
Description:

This part is the Special tube adaptor for Zimpure 3D printer fumes filter.
Zimpure is a filtration device that sucks all particles generated by 3D printer nozzles directly where they are generated.
All particles are then sent into a special filter that filters 99.9% of them.

The Zimpure device is linked to your 3D printer by a Tube.
This tube is connected to the 3D printer using a special adaptor compatible with your 3D printer model.

This thing is the Tube adaptor compatible with Scalar 3D printers: Scalar S, Scalar L, and Scalar XL Premium.

Special requirements

In order to print this thing you will need:

  • Supports
  • ABS or PETG material, as this part will be located very close to the hot end itself.

Special Thanks:

Thanks to Zimpure for the first version of this adaptor.
We made a few modifications to make it easier to adjust the height of the adaptor.

Special caution:

  • The Zimpure system V1 can be noisy
  • The tube is only 80cm long, so take special care where you place the device on big printer. For example, for Scalar XL Premium we found it easier to place at the top of the electronic box.
  • The noisy turbine system coupled with the long tube and the air flow going inside, can generate some vibrations on your X Carriage.
  • make sure to change your filtration cartridge every 500 printing hours.

Special note about .Rsdoc file

This file is to be opened using Design Spark Mechanical (free CAD tool)
